<HEADLINE>
<P>
A GENIUS FOR POLITICS, BUT WHAT ELSE?; 
</P>
<P>
MARIO CUOMO: HE HAS AN EXQUISITE SENSE OF TIMING AND WON'T RUN FOR PRESIDENT 
UNLESS HE'S SURE TO WIN. THAT DOESN'T MEAN HE CAN GOVERN. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MURRAY KEMPTON, Murray Kempton writes a syndicated column in New York. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Will Mario Cuomo run for President in 1992? The answer is simple and will 
persuade anyone who overlooks its slight defect of not being an answer at all. 
</P>
<P>
Mario Cuomo will run for President if he senses he will win. He won't if he 
senses he will lose. He will have judged correctly in either case. Those 
assessments of the political future that are un-useful speculations for the 
rest of us are dead certainties for him. He always knows. 
</P>
<P>
Cuomo's peculiar gift is a genius for politics, which is not, to be sure, the 
same thing as a genius for governing. When his wind is up as an orator, he can 
more than occasionally bemuse his auditors, not to say himself, into thinking 
him a lonely antagonist of destiny. But what he really is, instead, is 
destiny's favored messenger. 
</P>
<P>
On Labor Day, 1989, New York's Democratic mayoral primary was approaching its 
climax with most observers unconvinced that Edward Koch's official franchise 
for giving offense might not extend to another four years. Then Cuomo greeted 
the Labor Day marchers with the wickedly wistful expression of the hope that 
New York would find leaders of the sort who heal rather than wound. He cited 
David Dinkins and two other officeholders. He did not mention the incumbent 
mayor; it could be felt with resistless conviction that all was up for Koch. 
</P>
<P>
Two weeks ago, the governor roused the New York Daily News strikers with 
incandescences of solidarity. He closed the question while men of good will and 
bad alike were still struggling to keep it open. No sensible politician could 
conceivably thus flame for the oppressed if he could remotely imagine that the 
oppressor might have a chance to pay him back. 
</P>
<P>
I have one or two friends who have crossed the News picket line and many more 
who have refused to; and the abandonment of all hope of a happy ending for any 
of them is a bitter thought. But Cuomo can be trusted never to throw caution to 
the winds if he feels the faintest breath of a breeze in the air. There is no 
appealing his cool and sober judgment; he had but to strike the opening chord 
of destiny's overture to persuade the ear that the curtain will fall upon the 
death of the Daily News. 
</P>
<P>
There are complaints that Cuomo's views on the Persian Gulf crisis are 
inscrutable. They are likely to stay that way so long as the event itself 
remains so inscrutable that even destiny cannot think of the lines to prompt 
him. Our official policy seems to have arrived at a condition of incoherence 
that suggests management of the sort that puzzles itself as much as it does its 
antagonist. 
</P>
<P>
Uncertainties of this sort do not fit Cuomo's style, which depends upon 
exquisite subtleties of timing inapplicable to messy and unresolved situations. 
Economy of effort marks the genius for politics; its highest art is waiting 
until the candidate for disposal wanders to the edge of the abyss and then 
giving the unobtrusively slight shove that carries him all the way down to the 
coroner's verdict of suicide. 
</P>
<P>
That was the fashion of Cuomo's dealings with Koch and it apparently obtains 
for his dealings with the Daily News. It was also the fashion of Joe McCarthy's 
riddance by Dwight Eisenhower, who may have been our last President to combine 
an acute genius for politics with a considerable talent for governing when he 
had to -- and who at the same time contrived to keep both secret from observers 
thought wiser than he. 
</P>
<P>
A genius for politics never permits itself a calculated stroke without its 
proper disguise as the spontaneous expression of a heart that can be silent no 
longer. If Cuomo runs for President, he will win. If he doesn't, he would have 
lost. How do I know? I don't have to; Cuomo will. A genius for politics is that 
rarest of presences, the one that frees us from guessing for ourselves because 
it somehow knows for sure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Drawing, Mario Cuomo 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
<TYPE>
<P>
